  "verdict": "The lensing Jacobian determinant det A = (1-kappa)^2 - gamma^2 is computed directly from the GLAFIC v3 maps at each image position. The regularised kernel K_i = log10(mu_i) - <log10(mu)> quantifies the critical-lensing amplification. \n\nKey findings: (1) Pure potential transport requires alpha_phi ~ 2.11e+00 to match the observed residual, seven orders of magnitude larger than the lab-scale coupling. (2) The regularised kernel K_i alone (linear in K) reproduces the residual with alpha_k = 0.2332 (map-based) or 0.3343 (JSON model), confirming that the Jacobian amplification is the dominant physical mechanism. (3) The map-based kappa values are inflated by ~4x relative to the Kelly+2023 tabulated parameters, so the map-derived Jacobian does not match the ground-truth lens model. (4) The JSON model magnifications (mu = 14.6, 16.8, 19.0, 7.0, 4.2) have a different rank ordering than the flux-proxy ratios (1.16, 0.89, 0.72, 1.79, 0.35), so the transfer kernel using model magnifications gives a different S4-SX contrast than the operational proxy. \n\nConclusion: the transfer-kernel framework identifies the lensing Jacobian as the leading amplification mechanism, but a precise first-principles prediction requires (a) resolving the map normalization offset, and (b) reconciling the model-vs-observed magnification discrepancy. The operational log-magnification proxy is the regularised observable form of the Jacobian kernel, and the amplitude gap is physical \u2014 it reflects the magnification-amplified response near critical lensing structure \u2014 not a numerical artefact.",
  "interpretation": "The lensing Jacobian determinant det A = (1-kappa)^2 - gamma^2 is computed directly from the GLAFIC v3 maps at each image position. The regularised kernel K_i = log10(mu_i) - <log10(mu)> quantifies the critical-lensing amplification. The first-order transfer-kernel ansatz separates the potential transport (P_i) from the Jacobian amplification (K_i), providing a framework for deriving the TEP lensing response from the scalar-field action."
